I'll help you design a Matrix class in TypeScript that uses a flat array for storage while maintaining matrix operations through shapes/dimensions. This approach can indeed be more performant as it reduces memory overhead and can make better use of CPU cache.

Here's an implementation:

```typescript
class Matrix {
  private data: number[];
  private rows: number;
  private cols: number;

  constructor(rows: number, cols: number, data?: number[]) {
    this.rows = rows;
    this.cols = cols;

    if (data) {
      if (data.length !== rows * cols) {
        throw new Error('Data length must match matrix dimensions');
      }
      this.data = [...data];
    } else {
      // Initialize with zeros if no data provided
      this.data = new Array(rows * cols).fill(0);
    }
  }

  // Get value at position (i,j)
  get(i: number, j: number): number {
    this.validateIndices(i, j);
    return this.data[i * this.cols + j];
  }

  // Set value at position (i,j)
  set(i: number, j: number, value: number): void {
    this.validateIndices(i, j);
    this.data[i * this.cols + j] = value;
  }

  // Matrix multiplication
  multiply(other: Matrix): Matrix {
    if (this.cols !== other.rows) {
      throw new Error('Invalid matrix dimensions for multiplication');
    }

    const result = new Matrix(this.rows, other.cols);

    for (let i = 0; i < this.rows; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < other.cols; j++) {
        let sum = 0;
        for (let k = 0; k < this.cols; k++) {
          sum += this.get(i, k) * other.get(k, j);
        }
        result.set(i, j, sum);
      }
    }

    return result;
  }

  // Add two matrices
  add(other: Matrix): Matrix {
    if (this.rows !== other.rows || this.cols !== other.cols) {
      throw new Error('Matrices must have same dimensions for addition');
    }

    const result = new Matrix(this.rows, this.cols);

    // Direct array operation instead of nested loops
    for (let i = 0; i < this.data.length; i++) {
      result.data[i] = this.data[i] + other.data[i];
    }

    return result;
  }

  // Transpose matrix
  transpose(): Matrix {
    const result = new Matrix(this.cols, this.rows);

    for (let i = 0; i < this.rows; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < this.cols; j++) {
        result.set(j, i, this.get(i, j));
      }
    }

    return result;
  }

  // Helper method to validate indices
  private validateIndices(i: number, j: number): void {
    if (i < 0 || i >= this.rows || j < 0 || j >= this.cols) {
      throw new Error('Index out of bounds');
    }
  }

  // Get matrix dimensions
  get shape(): [number, number] {
    return [this.rows, this.cols];
  }

  // Get raw data
  get rawData(): number[] {
    return [...this.data];
  }

  // Pretty print matrix
  toString(): string {
    let result = '';
    for (let i = 0; i < this.rows; i++) {
      for (let j = 0; j < this.cols; j++) {
        result += this.get(i, j) + ' ';
      }
      result += '\n';
    }
    return result;
  }
}

// Usage example:
const m1 = new Matrix(2, 3, [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]);
const m2 = new Matrix(3, 2, [7, 8, 9, 10, 11, 12]);
const m3 = m1.multiply(m2);

console.log('Matrix 1:');
console.log(m1.toString());
console.log('Matrix 2:');
console.log(m2.toString());
console.log('Result of multiplication:');
console.log(m3.toString());
```

This implementation offers several advantages:

1. **Memory efficiency**: Uses a single flat array instead of nested arrays.

2. **Performance optimization**: Operations like addition work directly on the underlying array, avoiding nested loops where possible.

3. **Type safety**: TypeScript provides type checking and better IDE support.

4. **Flexible construction**: Can create matrices from raw data or initialize with zeros.

5. **Error handling**: Includes validation for matrix operations and bounds checking.

