Let me help you understand the best practices for handling different number types when working with WebAssembly APIs.

1. JavaScript Array Number Types:
- A regular JavaScript array of numbers (`Array<number>`) doesn't have a fixed type
- When passing to WebAssembly, you'll want to use TypedArrays for better performance and type safety
- JavaScript `Number` type is always a 64-bit floating-point (equivalent to `double` in C/C++)

2. TypedArray Options in JavaScript:
```javascript
// Integer Arrays
Int8Array        // 8-bit signed integer
Uint8Array       // 8-bit unsigned integer
Int16Array       // 16-bit signed integer
Uint16Array      // 16-bit unsigned integer
Int32Array       // 32-bit signed integer
Uint32Array      // 32-bit unsigned integer
BigInt64Array    // 64-bit signed integer
BigUint64Array   // 64-bit unsigned integer

// Floating Point Arrays
Float32Array     // 32-bit floating point
Float64Array     // 64-bit floating point
```

3. Best Practices for WebAssembly API Design:

a. Use explicit typing in your API:
```javascript
// Instead of this
function processNumbers(numbers) { ... }

// Do this
function processNumbers(numbers: Float64Array) { ... }
```

b. Create separate functions for different number types:
```javascript
// WebAssembly exports
exports.processFloat32Array = (array: Float32Array) => { ... }
exports.processFloat64Array = (array: Float64Array) => { ... }
exports.processInt32Array = (array: Int32Array) => { ... }
```

c. Use type conversion helpers:
```javascript
function convertToappropriateType(numbers: number[] | TypedArray) {
  if (numbers instanceof Float64Array) {
    return numbers;
  }
  return new Float64Array(numbers);
}
```

