- Performance: Smaller types might be more memory efficient but could be slower due to conversion overhead
- Precision: Be aware of potential precision loss when converting between types
- Endianness: WebAssembly uses little-endian byte order

7. Regular JavaScript Array to TypedArray Conversion:
```javascript
const regularArray = [1, 2, 3, 4];

// These will all work, but have different memory representations
const float64Array = new Float64Array(regularArray);  // Most precise
const float32Array = new Float32Array(regularArray);  // Less precise but smaller
const int32Array = new Int32Array(regularArray);      // Integer only
```

To answer your specific question: A regular JavaScript array of numbers will not be exactly equivalent to a Float64Array, although JavaScript numbers are 64-bit floating-point internally. You'll need to explicitly convert the array to a TypedArray for WebAssembly interaction. Float64Array is typically the safest choice if you need to preserve JavaScript number precision exactly.

