This following is the description of the Self-Harmonized CoT algorithm also  known as ECHO.

<algorithm>
Algorithm 1 Self-Harmonized CoT
Require: A set of questions Q, the number of demonstrations for unification k, number of iteration T and number of demonstration for the  output m
Ensure: Demonstration list D= [d(1) , . . . , d(m) ]
1: Encode each q in Q by Sentence-BERT ▷ Question Clustering
2: Cluster all the encoded question representations into k clusters
3: for each cluster i = 1, . . . , k do
4: Sort questions q(i) = [q(i)1 , q(i)2 , . . .] in the ascending order of the distance to the cluster center
5: end for
6: for each cluster i = 1, . . . , k do ▷ Demonstration Sampling
7: for each question q(i)j in q(i) do
8: Generate rationale r(i)j for q(i)j using Zero-Shot-CoT
9: if q(i)j , r(i)j satisfy selection criteria then
10: Add d(k) = q(k) ◦r(k)0 to D
11: break
12: end if
13: end for
14: end for
15: for each iteration t = 1, . . . , T do ▷ Demonstration Unification
16: for each demonstration d(i) in D do
17: Create prompt P with demonstrations D\d(i) in random order
18: Regenerate rationale r(i) new for question q(i) using Few-Shot-CoT
19: Update d(i) = q(i) ◦r(i) new to D
20: end for
21: end for
22: Keep the first m elements and drop the remaining elements from D.
23: return D
</algorithm>

