Based on my knowledge, there are several ways to run an npm command when files change:

1. Using `nodemon`:
   ```json
   {
     "scripts": {
       "watch": "nodemon --exec 'npm run your-command'"
     }
   }
   ```
   First install nodemon: `npm install --save-dev nodemon`

2. Using `npm-watch`:
   ```json
   {
     "watch": {
       "your-command": {
         "patterns": ["src"],
         "extensions": "js,jsx",
         "quiet": false
       }
     },
     "scripts": {
       "watch": "npm-watch"
     }
   }
   ```
   First install npm-watch: `npm install --save-dev npm-watch`

3. Using `chokidar-cli`:
   ```json
   {
     "scripts": {
       "watch": "chokidar \"src/**/*\" -c \"npm run your-command\""
     }
   }
   ```
   First install chokidar-cli: `npm install --save-dev chokidar-cli`

All these solutions should be added to your package.json file. Replace `your-command` with the actual npm script you want to run when files change.

